TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Role of Affective Experience in Work Motivation
AU  - Seo, Myeong-Gu
AU  - Barrett, Lisa Feldman
AU  - Bartunek, Jean M.
Y1  - 2004/07/01
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2004.13670972
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2004.13670972
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 423
EP  - 439
VL  - 29
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Based on psychological and neurobiological theories of core affective experience, we identify a set of direct and indirect paths through which affective feelings at work affect three dimensions of behavioral outcomes: direction, intensity, and persistence. First, affective experience may influence these behavioral outcomes indirectly by affecting goal level and goal commitment, as well as three key judgment components of work motivation: expectancy judgments, utility judgments, and progress judgments. Second, affective experience may also affect these behavioral outcomes directly. We discuss implications of our model.
AB  - Based on psychological and neurobiological theories of core affective experience, we identify a set of direct and indirect paths through which affective feelings at work affect three dimensions of behavioral outcomes: direction, intensity, and persistence. First, affective experience may influence these behavioral outcomes indirectly by affecting goal level and goal commitment, as well as three key judgment components of work motivation: expectancy judgments, utility judgments, and progress judgments. Second, affective experience may also affect these behavioral outcomes directly. We discuss implications of our model.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2004.13670972
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.2004.13670972
Y2  - 2026/04/24
