TY  - JOUR
T1  - Competing Through Innovation in Network Markets: Strategies for Challengers
AU  - Sheremata, Willow A.
Y1  - 2004/07/01
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2004.13670986
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2004.13670986
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 359
EP  - 377
VL  - 29
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Challengers can successfully compete against dominant firms in network markets through innovation. However, the type of innovation a challenger should compete with depends on characteristics of the market and technology. I develop a typology of product innovation to model expected returns from different types of innovation. This model indicates radical innovation can be more profitable than incremental innovation, incompatible innovation more profitable than compatible innovation, and radical-incompatible innovation more profitable?and less risky?than incremental-compatible innovation. Sometimes more risk is more prudent, given the market in play.
AB  - Challengers can successfully compete against dominant firms in network markets through innovation. However, the type of innovation a challenger should compete with depends on characteristics of the market and technology. I develop a typology of product innovation to model expected returns from different types of innovation. This model indicates radical innovation can be more profitable than incremental innovation, incompatible innovation more profitable than compatible innovation, and radical-incompatible innovation more profitable?and less risky?than incremental-compatible innovation. Sometimes more risk is more prudent, given the market in play.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2004.13670986
